[[Category:Formerly unidentified murder victims]] [[Category:1984 deaths]] [[Category:Crimes against sex workers]] [[Category:People murdered in Pennsylvania]] [[Category:20th-century births]] [[Category:American murder victims]] [[Category:Murdered sex workers]]

'''Ford's Grand Opera House''' was a major [[music venue]] in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], located on West Fayette Street between North Howard and [[Eutaw Street]]s. It was founded by theatre manager [[John T. Ford]] (also the owner of infamous [[Ford's Theatre]] in [[History of Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C.]] where President [[Abraham Lincoln]] was assassinated, April 14, 1865) and designed by architect [[James J. Gifford]]. The opera house/theatre opened to the public on October 2, 1871 with a show that included readings from Shakespeare's ''"[[As You Like It]]"'' as well as vocal and orchestral performances. Then owned by 1950s–60s era theatre magnate [[Morris A. Mechanic Theatre|Morris A. Mechanic]], it closed almost 93 years later with its last [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] show from [[New York City]], "[[Sondheim on Sondheim|Something Funny Happened on the Way to the Forum]]" in 1964. It was replaced three years later as the prime site for Baltimore live theatre patrons with the opening in the landmark of the new downtown redevelopment project of [[Charles Center]], the starkly modernistic [[Brutalist architecture|"Brutalist"]] architecture of the [[Morris A. Mechanic Theatre]] at the southwest corner of [[Charles Street (Baltimore)|Charles]] and Baltimore Streets, four blocks to the east.<ref>{{cite book|last=Scharf|first=John Thomas|title=History of Baltimore City and County|year=1881|publisher=Louis Everts|location=Philadelphia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6tF4AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA696&lpg=PA696&dq=ford's+grand+opera+house+baltimore&source=bl&ots=tcOR3A_eG9&sig=wgY9UnvcGsOrPT_FANPho6UI9jU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EavsT9HiFqXj0QHJ7JnTBw&ved=0CE4Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=ford's%20grand%20opera%20house%20baltimore&f=false}}</ref>
The Ford Opera house was later the site of newspaper publisher of the ''[[New York Tribune]]'', [[Horace Greeley]]'s nomination as the [[Liberal Republican Party (United States)|Liberal Republican Party]] candidate from a split Republican Party for the [[United States presidential election, 1872|1872 American Presidential election]] versus regular [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] candidate, incumbent 18th President, [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and [[1872 Democratic National Convention|Democratic candidate]] Seymour, who was reelected.
== Protests (1946-1952) == The allure of the theatre attracted many kinds of people. Starting in 1946, Civil Rights activists in Baltimore such as [[Adah Louise Killion Jenkins|Adah Jenkins]] began to picket the Ford’s Grand Opera House. This demonstration was a direct result of the Jim Crow policies at the time, which led to segregation in seating, accommodation, and ticket availability for people of colored skin. The Ford Theatre gave specific seating to African-Americans, often in the third row of the theatre. <ref>Parren Mitchell, Oral History. 1976. OH 8170, Governor Theodore McKeldin-Dr. Lillie May Jackson Project. Maryland Historical Society.</ref> During this period, Civil Rights activists were able to make an impact on the segregation policies of Baltimore’s theatres to the point where it was recognized by the NAACP. <ref>Brown, Milton P. Letter to Mr. and Mrs. Sidney Hollander. Sidney Hollander Papers, MS 2044, March 4, 1949, MdHS</ref>
After six years of protesting, Ford's Opera House desegregated in 1952.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=|title=After 6 Year At The Picket Line: MD's Ford Theatre Ends Separate Seating Policy|last=|first=|date=February 9, 1952|work=The Balto African American|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> Fords theatre had been operating under segregation since its opening in 1871. After multiple appeals to actors and other influential people in the community, officials in charge of the theatre agreed on the desegregation of the theatre, saying that it would add to the welfare of colored people and help aid in the betterment of race relations.<ref name=":0" /> To help end segregation in Ford's theatre, protestors enlisted the help of the NAACP, playwrights, actors, and more which proved to be very effective in bringing awareness to the community. <ref>Brown, Milton P. Letter to Mr. and Mrs. Sidney Hollander. Sidney Hollander Papers, MS 2044, March 4, 1949, MdHS</ref> Even Government officials found themselves speaking out against the segregation of Ford's theatre such as Governor McKeldin, when he called the segregation, offensive, illogical, and absurd.<ref>{{Cite news|title=McKeldin Takes Initiative: Gov. Calls For Probe Of Ford’s Theatre Bias|last=|first=|date=January 12, 1952|work=The Balto African-American|access-date=|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> ==References== {{reflist}} *{{cite book|title=New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians|chapter=Baltimore|last=Galkin|first=Elliott W.|author2=N. Quist|pages=611–612}} [[Category:Culture of Baltimore]] [[Category:Buildings and structures in Baltimore]] [[Category:1964 disestablishments in Maryland]] [[Category:Theatres completed in 1871]] [[Category:1871 establishments in Maryland]] [[Category:Event venues established in 1871]] ==External links== * [http://www.baltimorestyle.com/index.php/style/baltimore/baltimore_almost_broadway/ Baltimore Almost Broadway] * https://mdhs.org/sites/default/files/cxvj.pdf
